<div id="review_4195876636" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4195876636" />
    <a title="Jase" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/139294901-jase"><img alt="Jase" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1629548202p2/139294901.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4195876636?book_show_action=true">Aug 24, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jase" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jase" href="/user/show/139294901-jase">Jase</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4195876636" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer186315456031876874">I&apos;m not a particular fan of historical fiction nor am I a particular fan of mystery novels, though I have odd pockets of both that I cherish but this is a work mixing the two that I very much enjoyed and was as shocked to have done so more than any other reading experience I had.<br/><br/>If you like either of those genre or both you should give this a shot and I think what really brings it through is a good way into the novel it starts getting this thriller vibe that is very satisfying.<br/><br/>After reading it I</span>
  <span id="freeText186315456031876874" style="display:none">I'm not a particular fan of historical fiction nor am I a particular fan of mystery novels, though I have odd pockets of both that I cherish but this is a work mixing the two that I very much enjoyed and was as shocked to have done so more than any other reading experience I had.<br /><br />If you like either of those genre or both you should give this a shot and I think what really brings it through is a good way into the novel it starts getting this thriller vibe that is very satisfying.<br /><br />After reading it I thought I had found a rare (for me) book so I decided to check out other Pears' novels to get more, this being my introduction to him, I think a random paperback I picked up in paperback exchange place in Sardinia.<br /><br />Unfortunately, I was right about the uniqueness of this novel. I must have a half dozen more Pears books looking for that same authorial vibe that made this such a treat and forgive me for a crude turn of phrase, but he blew his load on An Instance of the Fingerpost. All of the other books were standard fare stuff that makes my first sentence in this review a truth about me, and the scholarship might be there but none of intrigue or thrill exist in those novels.<br /><br />Writing is hard. Pears gave us one great book. For that I'm grateful.</span>
  <a data-text-id="186315456031876874" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


